  <description type="morphology">Inflorescences &lt;rounded-corymbiform&gt;, 13–60-flowered, narrowly branched, without subsidiary branches. Flowers 10–15 mm diam.; sepals persistent, not enclosing capsule, 5, ovate-lanceolate to lanceolate, subequal, (2–)4–7 × 1–1.5 mm; petals 5, bright yellow, obovate-oblanceolate, 6–8 mm; stamens persistent, 60–80; ovary 3-merous, &lt;placentation parietal&gt;. Capsules ellipsoid to ovoid-ellipsoid, 3.5–6 × 2–4 mm. Seeds slightly carinate, 0.6–0.7 mm; testa scalariform. 2n = 18.</description>
  <description type="phenology">Flowering late summer (Jul–Sep).</description>
  <description type="habitat">Marshes, pond margins, wet ditches, bogs, coastal plain;</description>
  <description type="elevation">0–1000 m;</description>
  <description type="distribution">Conn., Del., Ga., Ill., Ind., Md., Mass., Mo., N.J., N.Y., N.C., Pa., R.I., S.C., Tenn., Va., W.Va.</description>
  <discussion>Hypericum adpressum is more herbaceous and rhizomatous than H. sphaerocarpum and has narrower capsules and smaller seeds.</discussion>
  <discussion>The plants with aerenchymatous tissue in the rhizome (var. spongiosum) are not taxonomically distinct but merely the result of a habitat-induced modification.</discussion>
